ment Synergies:** When the Space segment launches internal Starlink satellites, the company **does not recognize inter-segment revenue**. Instead, the costs are capitalized. Consequently, the Space segment\'s external revenue appears artificially lower relative to its operational scale, but the CODM recognizes its "foundational strategic value" in bolstering the growth of the Connectivity and AI segments. (This is why "Mass to Orbit" grows much faster than Space segment revenue—it includes internal deployments that drive the other segments).\n*   **Cross-Segment Capital Allocation Strategy:** The company\'s funding strategy relies on a self-reinforcing cycle of inter-segment dependency. Capital was initially raised to fund the Space segment. Once the Space segment began generating sustained positive Segment Adjusted EBITDA, those cash flows (along with external capital) were reinvested to build the Connectivity segment. Now, cash flows from these mature segments are being used to fund the massive, multi-year capital expenditures required for the newly acquired AI segment\'s compute infrastructure.\n*   **Shared Infrastructure & Supply Chain:** The segments share supply chain dependencies (e.g., advanced semiconductor fabrication for AI and Space/Connectivity hardware) and infrastructure, meaning resource allocation (like capital expenditures and R&D) must be managed holistically to support the broader ecosystem (e.g., Space R&D for Starship directly enables Connectivity and AI expansion).\n\n### Summary\nThe CODM does not view the segments in isolation. While **Segment Income from Operations** and **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** are the formal financial metrics used for reporting and baseline evaluation, the actual **resource allocation** is deeply influenced by the symbiotic relationship between the segments. The Space segment is deliberately resourced and utilized as the foundational infrastructure that enables the high-margin, recurring revenue of the Connectivity segment and the massive future scale of the AI segment.',
